description.value:
Currently if you have elements containing no content the highlighter removes the closing tag and auto closes the opening tag. I have found that this can cause rendering issues. At least in firefox.

For example say I have this code:
{code} 
<div id="test">
    <div id="test_child"></div>
</div>
<div id="test_2">
    Test 2
</div>
{code}

The current highlighter would remove the empty div resulting in.
{code:xml} 
<div id="test">
   <div id="test_child"/>
</div>
<div id="test_2">
    Test 2
</div>
{code}

Examining this dom tree in firebug results in the following structure. (test_2 incorrectly becomes a child of test)
{code:xml} 
<div id="test">
   <div id="test_child"></div>
   <div id="test_2">
        Test 2
   </div>
</div>
{code}

Currently Zend_Search_Lucene_Document_Html::getHtmlBody() calls $this->_doc->saveXML($bodyNodes->item($count); 
This replaces all empty tags with single tag versions.
saveXML() could take a second parameter LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG, which will expand empty tags and prevent this problem.

Here is a test script I ran, by modifying some lucene code, to compare the current output compared with LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG
{code:xml}
<?php
function test($htmlData) {    
    $doc = new DOMDocument();
    $doc->substituteEntities = true;
    $doc->loadHTML($html);
                    // It's an HTML fragment
    $doc->loadHTML('<html><head><META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=UTF-8"/></head><body>'
                         . iconv('UTF-8', 'UTF-8//IGNORE', $htmlData)
                         . '</body></html>');
    
    $xpath = new DOMXPath($doc);
    $bodyNodes = $xpath->query('/html/body')->item(0)->childNodes;
    
    echo "Input:\t\t\t";
    echo $htmlData;
    
    $outputFragments = array();
    for ($count = 0; $count < $bodyNodes->length; $count++) {
        echo "\nDefault:\t\t";
        echo $doc->saveXML($bodyNodes->item($count));

        echo "\nLIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG:\t";
        echo $doc->saveXML($bodyNodes->item($count), LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG);
    }
    
    echo "\n\n";
}

test('<div>Test</div>');
test('<div> </div>');
test('<div></div>');
test('<div>&nbsp;</div>');
test('<br/>');
test('<img src="/test.jpg" />');
test('<img src="/test.jpg">');
{code}

Output:
{code}
Input:                  <div>Test</div>
Default:                <div>Test</div>
LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG:      <div>Test</div>

Input:                  <div> </div>
Default:                <div> </div>
LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG:      <div> </div>

Input:                  <div></div>
Default:                <div/>
LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG:      <div></div>

Input:                  <div>&nbsp;</div>
Default:                <div>Â </div>
LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG:      <div>Â </div>

Input:                  <br/>
Default:                <br/>
LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG:      <br></br>

Input:                  <img src="/test.jpg" />
Default:                <img src="/test.jpg"/>
LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG:      <img src="/test.jpg"></img>

Input:                  <img src="/test.jpg">
Default:                <img src="/test.jpg"/>
LIBXML_NOEMPTYTAG:      <img src="/test.jpg"></img>
{code}

Obviously replacing all empty tags with {code}&nbsp;{code} Could be a workaround, but there may be other issues in doing this. 

Thanks
